  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Treating D-8 as Passive Investment</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">D-8 requires genuine business operations—you must run an actual company. Immigration checks that businesses are operational, have employees (ideally Korean), and conduct real commercial activity. "Parking" money in a shell company leads to renewal denial. If you want passive investment, choose F-5-5 (bonds) instead.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Korean Language Need</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While not required for investor visas initially, Korean becomes essential. Business dealings, government paperwork, banking—all primarily in Korean. Citizenship requires TOPIK Level 5 (advanced). Start learning immediately upon arrival. Those who don't learn Korean remain permanent outsiders in business and society.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Ignoring Tax Obligations</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Korea taxes worldwide income for residents. D-8 and F-5 holders are tax residents. Failure to file properly can jeopardize visa renewal and citizenship eligibility. Korean tax system is complex—hire Korean CPA from the start. Tax compliance is verified during visa renewals and citizenship applications.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Private Insurance Initially</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">NHI eligibility starts after 6 months. Medical emergencies happen—Korean hospitals provide excellent care but expect payment. Without insurance, serious treatment can cost tens of millions of won. International coverage for the first 6 months is essential, not optional.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Seoul Living Costs</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Housing in Seoul is extraordinarily expensive. Jeonse (lump-sum deposit) system requires KRW 300M-800M+ for decent apartments. Monthly rent alternatively runs KRW 2-4M+ for comfortable housing. International schools cost KRW 30-50M/year. Budget realistically—many investors are shocked by Seoul costs.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

