  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get Korean citizenship through investment?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, but indirectly. Investment visas provide residence that can lead to citizenship after 5 years. Citizenship requirements: 5+ years continuous residence, TOPIK Level 5 Korean proficiency, basic civics test, financial stability, and renouncing other citizenships (Korea generally doesn't allow dual citizenship for naturalized citizens).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What Korean language level do I need for investor visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Investor visas (D-8, F-5) don't require Korean proficiency. However, citizenship requires TOPIK Level 5 (advanced). Even without citizenship goals, Korean is practically essential for business and daily life. Most government services, banking, and business are conducted in Korean. Start learning immediately upon arrival.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I bring my family on investor visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Spouse and unmarried children under 18 can receive F-3 dependent visas. They can study (children) but need separate work permits to work. F-5 permanent residence includes family. Children may attend Korean public schools (free with NHI enrollment) or international schools (KRW 30-50M/year).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if my business fails?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          D-8 visa depends on maintaining business operations. If your business fails, you may need to: 1) Start new qualifying business, 2) Convert to different visa if eligible (F-2-7 points system, marriage visa, etc.), or 3) Leave Korea. F-5 permanent residence is more stable—you only need to maintain the investment amount, not necessarily business success.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does the Jeju Investment program work?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Jeju Island has special F-5-6 rules: invest KRW 500M+ in designated resort/leisure property (lower than mainland KRW 1.5B threshold). Must be specific approved developments. Provides F-5 permanent residence. Popular with Chinese investors. Property must be maintained; sale may affect visa status. Recent rule changes have tightened requirements—consult specialist.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the OASIS startup visa worth it?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          For tech entrepreneurs, yes. OASIS (government startup incubator) provides: lower investment requirements, fast-track visa processing, office space, mentoring, and networking. Must pass screening showing innovative business concept. Ideal for tech/software startups. More selective than standard D-8 but significantly better support infrastructure.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      South Korea offers one of Asia's most attractive investor pathways for those willing to make a real commitment. The D-8 visa provides entry at reasonable investment levels (~$75K), while F-5 permanent residence offers long-term stability. Most significantly, Korea provides a clear path to citizenship—rare among Asian developed economies.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The trade-offs are substantial: high living costs (especially Seoul), challenging language, competitive business culture, and complex bureaucracy. Korea rewards those who commit fully—learn the language, build genuine businesses, and integrate into society. Those seeking passive residence or English-speaking environments should look elsewhere (Thailand Elite, Singapore).
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      Healthcare through mandatory NHI is excellent and affordable. The first 6 months require private international insurance, then NHI provides comprehensive coverage. Supplemental Korean insurance can cover gaps. Overall healthcare costs are reasonable by developed-country standards.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        South Korea suits serious investors seeking developed-market stability, world-class healthcare, and eventual citizenship in Asia's fourth-largest economy. D-8 works for entrepreneurs building real businesses. F-5 suits those with KRW 300M+ for passive investment and immediate permanent residence. Commit to learning Korean and integrating—Korea rewards full commitment with an excellent quality of life.
      </p>
